3. CO2 Emissions

  1. 2017, 2018, and 2019 has the most missing values of 217.
missing_co2 <- data %>%
  filter(!is.na(time)) %>% 
  filter(is.na(co2) | is.na(co2_PC)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarize(num_missing = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_missing)) %>% 
  head(5)

  1. In the plot, I found that China has the sharpest increase and decrease between 2000 and 2020, followed by the US, while the UK’s co2 emissions position is at a stable and lowest value from 1960 to 2020. On the eve of 2020, all countries show declines of varying magnitude.
few_countries <- c('United States of America', 'China', 'India', 'Japan', 'United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland')

co2_select <- data %>% 
  filter(name %in% few_countries) %>% 
  group_by(name, time) %>% 
  summarize(co2 = sum(co2, na.rm =TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

ggplot(co2_select, aes(x = time, y = co2, color = name)) + geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Total CO2 Emissions Over Time", 
       x = "Year", 
       y = "Total CO2 Emissions (metric tons)")

  1. This figure shows that it is not China, but the United States of America that has the highest overall CO2 emissions per capita. Besides, rather than being a smooth and low emitter, the UK was in second place of my five chosen countries from 1960 to 1990, and was overtaken by Japan in the late 1990s. China and India have a relatively low emittion between 1960 to 2020, roughly lower than 2.5 tons per capita. While, China had a dramatic increase after 2000, and India had the lowest emissions of the five countries.

4. GDP per capita

  1. I saw that as GDP per capita increase, the Life expectancy also increases, which refers that there is a positive relationship between GDP percapita and life expectancy. There is no obvious relationship between total population and other variables, but the regions are roughly grouped together. For instance, the countries in Europe continent all has a relatively high life expectancy about 70 years and high GDP per capita in 1960. On the other side, the country in Africa are all with low GDP per capita and a low life expectany of less than 50 years.
data_1960 <- data %>% 
  filter(time == 1960) %>% 
  drop_na(region, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation)
  
ggplot(data_1960, aes(x = GDP_PC, y = lifeExpectancy, size = totalPopulation, color = region)) +
  geom_point()+
  scale_size(range = c(1, 10), breaks = c(1e6, 4e7, 6e7, 1e8, 3e8, 5e8),
             labels = c("1M", "40M", "60M", '100M', '300M', '500M')) +
  labs(title = "GDP per capita versus life expectancy in 1960",
       x = "GDP per Capita",
       y = "Life Expectancy",
       size = "Total Population",
       color = "Continent")

  1. This plot used 2019 data instead.

  1. Compared to 1960, The positive relationship between GDP per capita and life expectancy is still exists in 2016, but for all countries and regions, GDP per capita and life expectancy have risen significantly. The life expectancy in European countries in 2016 are around 80 years and GDP per capita reached values slightly above 90,000. The life expectancy in Africa are also increases from less than 50 years in 1960 to around 55-75 years.

  2. The result fits what I saw in plots that the life expectancy in all regions have rise significantly.

  1. I found out that the Africa has the largest average growth rate, while Europe has the smallest average growth rate.Americas and Oceania have similar average growth rate.
time_range <- c(1960, 2019)

life_exp_growth <- data %>%
  filter(time %in% time_range) %>%
  group_by(region, name) %>%
  arrange(name, time) %>%
  mutate(prev = lag(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(prev), !is.na(region)) %>%
  summarise(growth_rate = (lifeExpectancy - prev) / prev, .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  summarise(avg_growth_rate = mean(growth_rate)) %>% 
  arrange(avg_growth_rate)

life_exp_growth
## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   region   avg_growth_rate
##   <chr>              <dbl>
## 1 Europe             0.162
## 2 Americas           0.309
## 3 Oceania            0.325
## 4 Asia               0.493
## 5 Africa             0.563

us_relative_rank <- data %>%
  filter(time %in% time_range, !is.na(name), !is.na(lifeExpectancy)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  mutate(rank = rank(desc(lifeExpectancy)), num_countries = n_distinct(name), relative = rank / num_countries) %>% 
  filter(name == "United States of America") %>% 
  select(name, rank, num_countries, relative)
